The paper deals with the Closest Pair problem, which is a fundamental problem in Computational Geometry, and its complexity in the Euclidean metric. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves the construction of a dense bipartite graph, which suggests that it could be relevant to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The Strong Exponential Time Hypothesis (SETH) is used in the paper, which is a central hypothesis in computational complexity theory, making cs.CC (Computational Complexity) another likely sub-category. The paper also mentions locally dense codes, which are related to coding theory, indicating that cs.IT (Information Theory) could be a relevant sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the analysis of approximation algorithms, which suggests that it could be relevant to cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics).
